Interaction Effects

Interactions (continuous & categorical)

sim3: categorical predictor (x2) and continuous predictor (x1)

head(sim3)
ggplot(sim3, aes(x1, y)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = x2))

2 possible models for sim3 - + makes it so model estimates each effect independent of all others - * model can fit interaction

mod1 <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2, 
           data = sim3)
mod2 <- lm(y ~ x1 * x2, 
           data = sim3) 
# y = a_0 + a_1 * x1 + a_2 * x2 + a_12 * x1 * x2

To visualize these models, 2 new tricks: - pass both x1 and x2 for data_grid() - use gather_predictions() to generate predictions from both models simultaneously, adding prediction as a row - complement is spread_predictions(), which adds each prediction to a new column

grid <- sim3 %>%
  data_grid(x1, x2) %>%
  gather_predictions(mod1, mod2)
grid
# data_sim3 <- sim3 %>%
#   mutate(
#     mod1 = mad_fit_intercept + mad_fit_slope * data_sim1$x
#   )
ggplot(sim3, aes(x1, y, color = x2)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(data = grid, aes(y = pred)) +
  facet_wrap(~model)

Judging model using residuals - residuals in mod1 show pattern (which is bad)

sim3 <- sim3 %>% 
  gather_residuals(mod1, mod2)
head(sim3)
ggplot(sim3, aes(x1, resid, color = x2)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(model ~ x2)

Looking at non-linear data

Generating some non-linear data

sim5 <- tibble(
  x = seq(0, 3.5 * pi, length = 50),
  y = 4 * sin(x) + rnorm(length(x))*2
)
# plotting random points
ggplot(sim5, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point()

# creating a bunch of "polynomial" models with various degrees of freedom
mod1 <- lm(y ~ ns(x, df=1), data=sim5)
mod2 <- lm(y ~ ns(x, df=2), data=sim5)
mod3 <- lm(y ~ ns(x, df=3), data=sim5)
mod4 <- lm(y ~ ns(x, df=4), data=sim5)
mod5 <- lm(y ~ ns(x, df=5), data=sim5)
mod20 <- lm(y ~ ns(x, df=20), data=sim5)
grid <- sim5 %>%
  data_grid(x = seq_range(x, n= 50, expand = 0.1)) %>%
  gather_predictions(mod1, mod2, mod3, mod4, mod5, mod20, .pred = "y")
# plotting predictions
ggplot(sim5, aes(x,y)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(data = grid, color = "red") + 
  facet_wrap(~ model)

Looking at residuals

#calculating and plotting residuals
sim5 %>%
  gather_residuals(mod1, mod2, mod3, mod4, mod5, mod20) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x, resid)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~model)

Data Cleaning

daily <- flights %>% 
  mutate(date = make_date(year, month, day)) %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(n = n())
package bindrcpp was built under R version 3.3.2
# number of flights by day
ggplot(daily, aes(date, n)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Number of flights out of NYC by day")

Controlling by day of week

daily <- daily %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date, label=TRUE))
ggplot(daily, aes(wday, n)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(daily, aes(n)) +
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_wrap(~wday) +
  labs(title = "Number of flights by day of week")

Using model to remove pattern of flights by day of week.

# first fit model and display predictions over original data
mod <- lm(n ~ wday, data = daily)
grid <- daily %>%
  data_grid(wday) %>% 
  add_predictions(mod, "n")
# showing prediction
ggplot(daily, aes(n)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_wrap(~wday) + 
  geom_vline(data = grid, aes(xintercept = n), color = "red")

# now compute and visualize residuals
daily <- daily %>%
  add_residuals(mod)
ggplot(daily, aes(date, resid)) + 
  geom_ref_line(h=6) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Residuals after linear model for day of week")

daily2 <- daily
